msItem.title: Materia Medica
msItem.explicit: ... neach do ghabh hé an Gaidheilcc. F.i.n.i.t. Amen. Misi Gilla Coluim.

note.p: Dinneen lists one of the senses of dreann as "pain". As such it would seem that "drenn" in this text is likely to be taken as such, or, if not, would be the name of a respiratory disease.

The second word is simply ".m." in the MS. An instance of m in enclosing puncta was has been expanded as "muice" above but here, following O'Connor (2018) it has been understood to be abbreviating as "mathgamna".
A suspension stoke originally appeared over the tironian et (= "eter"?) but an attempt has been made to erase it.

The letter transcribed here as l has somewhat of amark over bottom of the letter that curls upwards. However, the present editors are of the opinion that only an l would render a sensible word in this context. Thus, it seems to have been a scribal slip of some sort that was corrected immediately and is hence transcribed here as the letter l.

note.p: Other MSS (O'Connor 2018: 85) add "& epaticum" at this point, which the sentence does indeed seem to require.

While there is no headword for this in eDIL, Dwelly or Teanglann.ie, the term gearr nimhe is given for petty spurge in tearma.ie. Furthermore, O'Connor (2018: 89) prints gerraneime as a single word. Thus, while it seems clear that the word is intended to mean "spurge" or "petty spurge" it is unclear whether this is a single word or two words in origin, and this whether the vowel between the rr and n is considered to be an epenthetic vowel or the aricle.
Other manuscripts stipulate that the herb should not be gathered during this period.
There is an "a" written below the "i" of "inat", but there is nowhere for it to be cogently inserted.

The characters here are somewhat unclear but the present editors postulate that the scribe wrote an i followed by an r and upon this attempted to correct it by making it an rr ligature. It has consequently been emended to "bru" in the present edition.

The present editors are unaware of attestations of gallúinech similar to the one printed here. Furthermore if the scribe of the exemplar had forgotten to write u in the midde of this word and later added it superscript it is easy to imagine how a form containing -rn- was understood by our scribe and appears here.
Other MSS (O'Connor 2018: 103) specify here that the mixture is to be applied "fona cosaib" (on the legs)
A different hand later added a lenited g above this c but the current reading is understood to be correct by the present editors.
The insertion is added in a different ink but seems to still be in the hand of the main scribe.
According to O'Connor (2018: 714),this is a term for red lichen.
The "et reliqua" has been added in a different ink but apparently in the same hand.
In O'Connor (2018), "piletra" is traced back to Lat. "baletri", a synonym of "serpillum" (wild thyme). In the entry on "serpillum", "piletra" is treated as the Gaelic term.
